            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Vikram Volkova is a product of academic curiosity and Cold War romance. His father, an Indian physicist, met his mother, a Russian literature scholar, at a conference in Berkeley in the late 1960s. They fell in love over debates on Tagore and Tolstoy, eventually settling near the university. Vikram grew up in a home where the shelves overflowed with books and the air hummed with English, Hindi, and Russian. This environment instilled in him a profound respect for information and the systems used to organize it.\n\nHe pursued an undergraduate degree in history but found himself more fascinated by the burgeoning internet of the early 1990s. While his peers saw a chaotic network, Vikram saw a library in desperate need of a card catalog. This revelation led him to a Master of Library and Information Science, where he specialized in digital preservation just as the field was being born.\n\nHis career began at a San Francisco university library during the dot-com boom. While tech evangelists promised a paperless future, Vikram focused on the practical, unglamorous work of building the infrastructure to archive it. His key turning point was convincing the university to fund a massive digitization project for its photographic archives in 1999, a move that seemed esoteric then but proved visionary. This success cemented his reputation, leading to his current role as Director of Digital Archives.\n\nFor the last twenty years, Vikram has lived in the same rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Sunset with his partner, a landscape architect named Caleb. He treasures his daily commute on the N Judah, a quiet time for reading before confronting the digital demands of his day. His life is a study in ordered calm: early morning walks in Golden Gate Park, meticulous work preserving digital history, and evenings spent cooking and discussing art and politics with Caleb.\n\nVikram's connection to San Francisco is deep; he sees it not just as a hub of innovation but as a living archive of culture, one he is committed to protecting. His primary aspiration is to launch an open-access initiative, making the city\u2019s digital history freely available to all. Personally, he dreams of one day taking a sabbatical to travel the ancient Silk Road, tracing the original, analog routes of information exchange."
